and Identity Politics in Gheorghiu-Dej's Romania, 1956-64 -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aDeals with the period of takeover and of 'high Stalinism' in Eastern Europe (1945-1955). These years are considered to be fundamentally characterized by institutional and ideological transfers based upon the premise of radical transformism and of cultural revolution. Both a balance-sheet and a politico-historical synthesis that reflects the archival and thematic novelties which came about in the field of communism studies after 1989. Contains contributions analyzing various aspects related these topics for each country of the former Soviet bloc (with the exception of Albania). The essays are based on new archival research, some are reassessments of the author's previous research and others are critical appraisals of the specific literature published on issues related to the main topic. A path-breaking comparative framework for interpreting the relationship between late Stalinism and the communist takeovers in former Eastern Europe. A bonus for the volume is that it also provides detailed, sectorial analyses for the Romanian case, something that the field paritcularly lacks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCommunismzEurope, EasternxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Fascism & Totalitarianism.2bisacsh  aCold War, Communism, Foreign relations, Political studies.1 aAbrams, Bradley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnelly, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrincu, Dorin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca